snippet.textDisplay:
I really appreciate the scenes on the astartes' HQ ship with the sphere and the psycher. I love how that scene depicted urgency through almost only pure body language.
And also it just further proves the professionalism of astartes as a military unit (the assault squad done that already, but these guys hammer it down).



For the entirety of the series so far we have not seen astartes being particularly bothered about anything. The entire assault on the ship was carried out slowly and methodically, with astartes pretty much strolling their way to victory, occasionaly breaking into casual sprint in order to be faster than their enemies. Even the battle with those 2 guardians wasn't exactly something they seemed to be bothered about: they were moving and acting fast because they had to in order to win against a very quick and nimble opponent. It was just another job to them.


And that's how it was to the officers too. 0:48 We see the 2 officers entering the chamber, and crossing their hands. They just wait, patiently. They are almost relaxed, really.
Including the 3rd guard in the room, who is also doesn't seem to be particularly on edge either. 1:00 He holds his bolter almost casually. And yet... His eyes appear to be dead-set on the psycher.


3:54 The psycher hears the spheres talking and realizes that they are planing something. Something that could put the squad in danger.
4:25 He turns his head in urgent manner - a gesture immediately returned by the astartes officer, as he gives psycher his full attention.
The psycher speaks, but there is no tact or manners as he, after what i assume to be minutes of eerie silence, adresses his superior (in more ways than one) and he only says what the officer needs to hear: "RETURN THEM IMMEDIATELY".


In some other piece of media this could be turned into a drama for a second, with the officer going "why?" and maybe even starting to argue with the psycher. But this is not another piece of media...
4:28 It takes a fraction of a second for the officer astartes to consider the information he was just given. He does not even adresses the psycher back.
His patient posture is broken in a flash as he commands the 3rd guard in the room to get moving.
4:31 I find the guard's body language almost shocking. This is the first time in the entire series we see astartes being something close to anxious. There is also something horrifying about watching a suit of armor this size and weight to just make a 180 degree turn and bolt from a stand-still.
The 2nd officer also drops his relaxed stance.
4:40 you can see 2nd officer reaching for his gun. In any other universe, reaching for your gun when your supposed ally starts acting weird could be considered an overreaction. Here... Its a perfectly rational precaution.
4:58 The precaution proves to be correct. In my faulty memory i remember the 2nd officer almost jumping into the frame out of nowhere, but that's not the case. He simply grabs his gun, and takes the shots. Not in panic, not casually. Professionally.






I wish media would more often depict military units like this. Not just astartes... In general. So sick of watching incompetence - this in comparison is a goddamn joy to watch.

snippet.textDisplay: I found this very anticlimactic. After astartes 4, which was one of the best things I ever seen, I was hoping for a serious showdown against a mutant or daemon.. something to deliver on the suspense and tension established in the other episodes, or at least some finality in line with the ruthless no nonsense efficiency of these marines, be it clear cut success or failure.  Instead it's just some lame ball that mumbles some shit, eats the marines, and then a nonsensical cliffhanger.  I think I get the intent of what you guys were trying to do thematically, but it just fell flat to me and feels totally off from the first 4.  Otherwise, still top of the line production quality.

snippet.textDisplay: I know extremely little of the Warhammer universe. I found these videos from a Corridor feature. This has since become one of my favorite animated series on Youtube. I was able to understand every single story beat, moment-to-moment motivation, the relationship of each character to every other, etc. without one bit of exposition. I went into this with barely any prior knowledge, and by the end there was not one instant I felt I didn't understand. I'm curious about the world now, obviously, but this is some really masterful visual storytelling. Not to mention some of the most impressive visuals and sound design I've seen on this whole site. Incredible work, all around.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is seriously the best 40k thing I have ever seen, I find that it always try so hard to portray the bleakness and the badassery, but this is just effortlessly doing so, no over the top audio quips and oneliners, no bullshit super-hero-landing-poses, just true, undying Astartes grit with zero fucks to give. I just watched through all the episodes in one fell swoop and you should be proud of yourself, the aesthetics, the sound, and all the little things, the guys cloak moving because of the big gun in the ventilation shafts made the hairs on my arms stand.

10/10, would die for the God-Emperor again.
